buginformation.description:
I have a '.cif' file and in the Eclipse ESCET IDE this is opened by the CIF Text Editor (editor id `org.eclipse.escet.cif.texteditor.CifTextEditor`) by
                default.

                If I configure in plugin_customization.ini' the following:

                org.eclipse.ui.workbench/LARGE_DOC_SIZE_FOR_EDITORS=1048576

                Then files larger than 1 MiB don't open directly, but instead I get a dialog to select an alternative editor. If I then select the 'Text Editor' internal editor and
                click 'OK', it still opens with the 'CIF Text Editor', and not the 'Text Editor'.

                I looked in the source code and found the functionality in org.eclipse.ui.internal.WorkbenchPage.busyOpenEditor(IEditorInput, String, boolean, int, IMemento,
                boolean):

                ```
                IEditorDescriptor desc = getWorkbenchWindow().getWorkbench().getEditorRegistry().findEditor(editorId);
                if (desc != null !desc.isOpenExternal() isLargeDocument(input)) {
                desc = getAlternateEditor();
                if (desc == null) {
                // the user pressed cancel in the editor selection dialog
                return null;
                }
                }
                if (desc == null) {
                throw new PartInitException(NLS.bind(WorkbenchMessages.EditorManager_unknownEditorIDMessage, editorId));
                }
                ```

                If the file is large, the dialog is shown by 'getAlternateEditor' and it returns the proper new 'IEditorDescriptor' and this is put into 'desc'. However, 'editorId'
                is not updated to 'org.eclipse.ui.DefaultTextEditor', but remains 'org.eclipse.escet.cif.texteditor.CifTextEditor'. The CIF Text Editor is then still opened.

                I think this can be resolved by changing:

                ```
                desc = getAlternateEditor();
                if (desc == null) {
                // the user pressed cancel in the editor selection dialog
                return null;
                }
                ```

                to

                ```
                desc = getAlternateEditor();
                if (desc == null) {
                // the user pressed cancel in the editor selection dialog
                return null;
                }
                editorId = desc.getId();
                ```

                The 'editorId' is subsequently used when creating the editor part.

                Does this make sense?

Clicking on NotificationPopup doesn't reveal the parent window.

                NotificationPopup has absolute positioning and is always shown on the top of desktop environments windows stack. If there are any 3rd windows on the top of the
                parent window, it is not clear to what window/app the popped-up notification belongs to. On clicking on the header of notification nothing happens. This is
                confusing.

                In order to reproduce this one can use the following handler (to trigger notification on user action, e.g. icon click):

                import org.eclipse.core.commands.AbstractHandler;
                import org.eclipse.core.commands.ExecutionEvent;
                import org.eclipse.core.commands.ExecutionException;
                import org.eclipse.jface.layout.GridDataFactory;
                import org.eclipse.jface.notifications.AbstractNotificationPopup;
                import org.eclipse.swt.SWT;
                import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Composite;
                import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Display;
                import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Label;

                public class SampleHandler extends AbstractHandler {

                @Override
                public Object execute(ExecutionEvent event) throws ExecutionException {
                showNotification();
                return null;
                }

                private void showNotification() {
                if (Display.getCurrent() == null) {
                Display.getDefault().asyncExec(new Runnable() {
                @Override
                public void run() {
                showNotification();
                }
                });
                return;
                }
                try {
                Thread.sleep(10000); // time to open 3rd app. windows
                } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                e.printStackTrace();
                }
                NotificationPopup notificationPopup = new NotificationPopup(Display.getCurrent(), "header text",
                "Lorem Ipsum is simply dummy text of the printing and typesetting industry. Lorem Ipsum has been the industry's standard dummy text ever since the 1500s, when an
                unknown printer took a galley of type and scrambled it to make a type specimen book. It has survived not only five centuries, but also the leap into electronic
                typesetting, remaining essentially unchanged. It was popularised in the 1960s with the release of Letraset sheets containing Lorem Ipsum passages, and more recently
                with desktop publishing software like Aldus PageMaker including versions of Lorem Ipsum.");
                notificationPopup.open();
                }

                public class NotificationPopup extends AbstractNotificationPopup {

                private String fText;
                private String fTitle;

                public NotificationPopup(Display display, String title, String text) {
                super(display);
                this.fTitle = title;
                this.fText = text;
                }

                @Override
                protected void createContentArea(Composite parent) {
                Label contentLabel = new Label(parent, SWT.WRAP);
                contentLabel.setText(fText);
                GridDataFactory.fillDefaults().grab(true, false).align(SWT.FILL,
                SWT.BEGINNING).applyTo(contentLabel);
                }

                @Override
                protected String getPopupShellTitle() {
                return fTitle;
                }

                }
                }

                Expected behavior:
                Popup parent window should be shown (brought upfront) on clicking on NotificationPopup.
